<br>
Yes Satan can put thoughts into our mind because we are told to put on the helmet of salvation so that we can deflect the poisoned darts from the enemy. Whether he can read our thoughts is debatable. He has however had a long time to study us and know us very well so maybe it is not that important whether he can read them or not. He has had enough time to work them out in all of the situations that we get ourselves into and he watches how we react to his ideas he puts to us. I think that it is rather demons that speak to us rather than Satan although he must give us special attention sometimes if we are a threat to him. But he cannot be in more than one place at the same time.<br>
<br>
I agree with dd that we can test what we think we hear with what scripture says but for day to day listening we must know the voice of Jesus and recognize it because we know Him to that extent that we straight away are confirmed in our spirit and anyway we know the sort of things that He *might* say in the same way that we know what our marriage partner will say because we have learned their thought pattern and their opinions.<br>
<br>
But there is a danger of relying too much on checking with scripture and it is indeed possible to know God's voice without having a copy of the Bible. The early church did not have one for hundreds of years and even if they did they would not be able to read it and which version anyway? There are still languages which have not had it translated into, so there must be a bigger answer for what the Word of God is. Actually it is Jesus. If we do have scriptures though, we certainly need to know them, but not as our ultimate authority. That must be Jesus and hearing Him speak to us. If we are confused about whether it is Him then the answer is not to study the scriptures more but to get to know Him more. We do not find eternal life in the Bible but they witness to this life as the writers also were in the same spirit.<br>
<br>
